1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:07,950 --> 00:00:09,420
I look good in that photo.

3
00:00:09,850 --> 00:00:10,850
It's not about the photo.

4
00:00:12,150 --> 00:00:13,650
It's about what you say in it.

5
00:00:14,350 --> 00:00:18,410
So who would have expected the lady from the women's magazine to ask such tricky questions?

6
00:00:18,750 --> 00:00:21,250
Like what's your favorite book?

7
00:00:21,750 --> 00:00:25,080
Well, I expected her to ask what my favorite color is.

8
00:00:25,080 --> 00:00:25,600
I'd know that.

9
00:00:26,050 --> 00:00:27,880
But "Doggy and Kitty."

10
00:00:28,150 --> 00:00:29,920
Nothing better came to mind.

11
00:00:29,920 --> 00:00:31,480
And that Božena Němcová wrote it?

12
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:35,050
Well, now I also know it was Karel Čapek.

13
00:00:35,960 --> 00:00:36,500
Josef.

14
00:00:39,270 --> 00:00:39,810
Tomáš.

15
00:00:40,450 --> 00:00:42,430
You are an absolute cultural barbarian.

16
00:00:42,650 --> 00:00:44,050
Well, that's an exaggeration.

17
00:00:47,550 --> 00:00:52,250
The last thing I saw in the theater was The Bagpiper of Strakonice.

18
00:00:52,850 --> 00:00:54,650
That's a typo, I didn't say that.

19
00:00:55,250 --> 00:00:57,750
In parentheses, which he indeed said.

20
00:00:57,950 --> 00:00:59,150
Editor's note.

21
00:01:00,450 --> 00:01:02,650
They write that you're a candidate for that parade.

22
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:06,950
Maybe I shouldn't give interviews, you see.

23
00:01:07,150 --> 00:01:09,430
For now it'd be enough if you occasionally went to the theater.

24
00:01:09,950 --> 00:01:13,150
Or read something more serious than a detective novel.

25
00:01:14,750 --> 00:01:15,750
Like The Trial.

26
00:01:16,750 --> 00:01:17,650
Alright then.

27
00:01:18,350 --> 00:01:20,150
And who wrote it?

28
00:01:50,950 --> 00:01:52,350
Tomáš, this can't go on like this.

29
00:01:53,350 --> 00:01:54,950
You're embarrassing both of us.

30
00:01:55,450 --> 00:01:56,850
How both of us?

31
00:01:57,150 --> 00:01:59,150
Everyone knows I'm your manager.

32
00:02:00,350 --> 00:02:03,610
Unlike you, I move in cultural circles.

33
00:02:04,050 --> 00:02:06,930
Well, I don't exactly associate with nothing but idiots either.

34
00:02:07,250 --> 00:02:11,750
Says the man whose brother thinks the most famous book in the world is the Bible.

35
00:02:12,950 --> 00:02:18,650
Today I'm going to a Thuringian surrealist exhibition opening with my three friends, and they're critics.

36
00:02:18,710 --> 00:02:19,350
Do you understand?

37
00:02:20,550 --> 00:02:25,890
If they've read that you don't know who wrote Doggy and Kitty, they'll make fun of me all evening.

38
00:02:25,890 --> 00:02:27,910
Educated women don't read Blonde magazine.

39
00:02:29,140 --> 00:02:29,720
Obviously.

40
00:02:29,900 --> 00:02:30,480
Hey.

41
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:35,050
Hey, our Czech teacher is sending you Doggy and Kitty, do you know why?

42
00:02:38,450 --> 00:02:39,350
Wonderful.

43
00:02:44,450 --> 00:02:45,150
What's wrong with her?

44
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:47,000
Ozzák ticked her off.

45
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:51,150
Josef.

46
00:02:52,750 --> 00:02:53,510
Where are you going now?

47
00:02:54,350 --> 00:02:56,590
We have parenting and sex ed this afternoon.

48
00:02:56,590 --> 00:02:56,910
What?

49
00:02:57,690 --> 00:02:58,550
What do you mean what?

50
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:01,050
Well, nothing.

51
00:03:01,150 --> 00:03:02,380
You got a problem with that?

52
00:03:02,550 --> 00:03:04,050
No, no, no.

53
00:03:04,850 --> 00:03:05,550
Well, I'm off.

54
00:03:05,600 --> 00:03:07,710
And you have to go?

55
00:03:09,450 --> 00:03:10,450
It's mandatory.

56
00:03:11,350 --> 00:03:11,950
Sure.

57
00:03:12,350 --> 00:03:13,550
We all go together.

58
00:03:14,350 --> 00:03:15,850
Wait, all of you?

59
00:03:16,150 --> 00:03:17,950
Like boys and girls together?

60
00:03:18,450 --> 00:03:20,050
No, we have it separately.

61
00:03:20,250 --> 00:03:21,410
Well, at least that.

62
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:23,290
I'm kidding.

63
00:03:25,090 --> 00:03:25,630
Right.

64
00:03:27,510 --> 00:03:28,150
Hello.

65
00:03:28,270 --> 00:03:29,710
Ivuška, I thought it was the banana.

66
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:33,100
But the boys were supposed to have the banana, what would you be doing with a banana?

67
00:03:33,650 --> 00:03:36,240
Well, I'm not going to listen to this.

68
00:03:36,450 --> 00:03:36,950
Oh, I must have written it down wrong.

69
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:40,720
So what were we supposed to have?

70
00:03:41,250 --> 00:03:43,240
A doll, I'll be changing its diaper.

71
00:03:43,250 --> 00:03:46,850
But I already told Lexa that he should have the doll.

72
00:03:48,250 --> 00:03:48,950
Man, I'd never have believed this is a school aid.

73
00:03:52,630 --> 00:03:53,470
Her name is Lída.

74
00:03:54,350 --> 00:03:55,500
Where'd you get it?

75
00:03:55,550 --> 00:03:57,050
Uncle Horvát got it for us.

76
00:03:57,350 --> 00:03:59,750
Lexa, the doll is mine.

77
00:04:01,020 --> 00:04:02,000
You have the banana.

78
00:04:02,290 --> 00:04:02,910
Damn.

79
00:04:12,560 --> 00:04:16,220
You're really fun to be around.

80
00:04:16,760 --> 00:04:18,220
Hang on, this is interesting.

81
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:20,450
There's a great recipe here.

82
00:04:22,650 --> 00:04:23,150
Hey.

83
00:04:23,330 --> 00:04:23,630
Hey.

84
00:04:26,650 --> 00:04:27,150
What've you got?

85
00:04:27,450 --> 00:04:28,850
Pajerová gave this to me for you.

86
00:04:29,350 --> 00:04:30,650
She says you should read it.

87
00:04:31,950 --> 00:04:32,950
I have The Trial.

88
00:04:33,350 --> 00:04:34,250
Also a cookbook?

89
00:04:34,450 --> 00:04:35,430
What cookbook?

90
00:04:35,450 --> 00:04:37,110
Doggy and Kitty is not a cookbook.

91
00:04:37,270 --> 00:04:38,370
There's an awesome recipe for cake in here.

92
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:40,660
But it's a fairy tale for children.

93
00:04:41,540 --> 00:04:42,040
By Čapek.

94
00:04:42,870 --> 00:04:43,370
Bro.

95
00:04:43,950 --> 00:04:45,830
Fairy tales have princesses and dragons.

96
00:04:45,830 --> 00:04:47,090
Cookbooks have recipes.

97
00:04:47,450 --> 00:04:49,350
And this is a recipe.

98
00:04:49,750 --> 00:04:51,610
Simona, please, give it to me.

99
00:04:51,610 --> 00:04:53,970
I just feel like the kitty made a mistake here.

100
00:04:53,970 --> 00:04:59,950
It says here, when you put only good things together, something bad comes out of it, which is nonsense.

101
00:05:01,950 --> 00:05:06,850
For God's sake, Ozzák, when you mix rum, beer, Fernet, and absinthe, you think it'll be good?

102
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:07,090
Wait.

103
00:05:08,050 --> 00:05:10,450
You know the recipe for a Braník Bomb?

104
00:05:12,350 --> 00:05:14,140
I was already afraid someone would leak it.

105
00:05:14,250 --> 00:05:15,750
We'll make a million off that one day.

106
00:05:16,450 --> 00:05:17,430
One Bomb, please.

107
00:05:17,930 --> 00:05:18,510
Bye.

108
00:05:24,960 --> 00:05:25,540
Hey.

109
00:05:26,950 --> 00:05:28,520
I forgot my keys.

110
00:05:30,750 --> 00:05:31,550
What did they have at school?

111
00:05:31,700 --> 00:05:32,280
Boring stuff.

112
00:05:33,350 --> 00:05:34,150
How boring?

113
00:05:34,750 --> 00:05:38,320
Well actually, the PE teacher and the Czech teacher demonstrated interrupted intercourse.

114
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:38,900
What?

115
00:05:40,250 --> 00:05:42,170
Iva, now you're really exaggerating.

116
00:05:42,350 --> 00:05:43,950
You're such a prude.

117
00:05:44,350 --> 00:05:45,730
I'm just a different generation.

118
00:05:46,050 --> 00:05:48,310
They didn't tell us about these things in school.

119
00:05:48,310 --> 00:05:48,890
They did.

120
00:05:49,250 --> 00:05:49,830
All the time.

121
00:05:49,830 --> 00:05:53,620
I mean the teachers, not the girls from the dorm.

122
00:05:53,850 --> 00:05:55,200
Teachers said it too.

123
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:55,840
Enough.

124
00:05:56,650 --> 00:05:57,850
Did Saša handle it?

125
00:05:58,150 --> 00:06:01,650
Mostly yes, but then she fainted when she saw the banana.

126
00:06:03,050 --> 00:06:04,030
That's not possible.

127
00:06:04,350 --> 00:06:05,590
She knows what a banana is.

128
00:06:05,950 --> 00:06:07,050
There was a condom on it.

129
00:06:07,450 --> 00:06:10,770
Oh, I was worried you were making me out to be a bad mother again.

130
00:06:11,250 --> 00:06:11,950
Well, gotta run.

131
00:06:14,150 --> 00:06:15,250
Poor Saša.

132
00:06:15,470 --> 00:06:17,590
Someone should talk to her about these things.

133
00:06:17,870 --> 00:06:19,150
Don't look at me.

134
00:06:19,430 --> 00:06:20,950
You know I'm not good at these things.

135
00:06:21,190 --> 00:06:22,230
And you think I am?

136
00:06:25,250 --> 00:06:26,050
Don't even forget it.

137
00:06:26,850 --> 00:06:31,360
If it weren't for me, Ivuška would know absolutely nothing about these things to this day.

138
00:06:31,550 --> 00:06:33,100
Don't even remind me.

139
00:06:33,150 --> 00:06:34,950
I had to tell her everything myself.

140
00:06:35,350 --> 00:06:39,650
The poor thing had a head full of questions and nobody told her anything.

141
00:06:40,050 --> 00:06:45,280
She was seven and she only asked you if a bee is the wife of a bumblebee.

142
00:06:45,750 --> 00:06:47,700
And you got that wrong too, by the way.

143
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:49,000
Don't underestimate me all the same.

144
00:06:49,180 --> 00:06:50,180
Everything ended up on me.

145
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:50,980
Well, there you go.

146
00:06:51,160 --> 00:06:51,640
What?

147
00:06:52,150 --> 00:06:54,110
If you did it before, with Saša it'll be a piece of cake.

148
00:06:54,190 --> 00:06:54,810
She's smart.

149
00:06:54,890 --> 00:06:55,950
This is out of the question.

150
00:06:56,450 --> 00:06:58,010
You can't do this one thing for me.

151
00:06:58,010 --> 00:07:00,230
Just take her aside and tell her the same thing you told Iva.

152
00:07:00,370 --> 00:07:01,510
You'll be back in fifteen minutes.

153
00:07:01,610 --> 00:07:03,550
But I didn't actually talk to Iva about it, damn it.

154
00:07:03,770 --> 00:07:04,390
But you said you did.

155
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:06,950
But I handled it by correspondence.

156
00:07:09,850 --> 00:07:10,750
How could you?

157
00:07:12,930 --> 00:07:13,330
By correspondence.

158
00:07:13,550 --> 00:07:14,610
It means by letters.

159
00:07:15,470 --> 00:07:15,870
Oh.

160
00:07:17,050 --> 00:07:18,250
What do you mean by letters?

161
00:07:18,650 --> 00:07:22,850
Well, I sent her letters and in them I explained everything.

162
00:07:23,950 --> 00:07:26,850
I signed them as Auntie Marta.

163
00:07:27,150 --> 00:07:30,330
That was you?

164
00:07:30,330 --> 00:07:31,450
You know about it?

165
00:07:32,350 --> 00:07:34,650
Ivuška was scared some pervert was writing to her.

166
00:07:34,750 --> 00:07:37,150
I didn't want to stress her out.

167
00:07:38,770 --> 00:07:39,230
Dad.

168
00:07:45,430 --> 00:07:46,970
They showed the older kids some movie apparently.

169
00:07:47,070 --> 00:07:48,010
I don't know why not us.

170
00:07:48,250 --> 00:07:50,090
If they showed a movie, it'd be a piece of cake.

171
00:07:50,430 --> 00:07:51,790
Iva, come on.

172
00:07:52,450 --> 00:07:57,050
We just had some old hag with a mustache telling us our bodies are blossoming.

173
00:07:59,000 --> 00:07:59,460
Yeah.

174
00:08:00,660 --> 00:08:02,640
I imagined your body blossoming.

175
00:08:03,060 --> 00:08:03,960
Stop it.

176
00:08:04,380 --> 00:08:05,540
You imagine me?

177
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:07,320
Lexa.

178
00:08:07,950 --> 00:08:09,920
No wait, because I totally imagine you too.

179
00:08:09,920 --> 00:08:10,300
Out.

180
00:08:11,450 --> 00:08:12,940
Fine, I'll go imagine you somewhere else.

181
00:08:13,550 --> 00:08:14,240
No, no, not that either.

182
00:08:14,450 --> 00:08:16,250
Great, so I'll stay here.

183
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:18,460
I can imagine you and look at you at the same time.

184
00:08:19,020 --> 00:08:21,400
Iva, what if they show us the movie next time?

185
00:08:21,480 --> 00:08:22,480
That's pretty likely.

186
00:08:23,250 --> 00:08:24,100
I won't be there.

187
00:08:24,450 --> 00:08:25,540
You're a case too.

188
00:08:25,750 --> 00:08:27,550
One worse than the other.

189
00:08:28,450 --> 00:08:29,950
And you stop it right now.

190
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:30,410
Stop what?

191
00:08:30,410 --> 00:08:32,550
What will the movie be about?

192
00:08:32,990 --> 00:08:33,470
Guess.

193
00:08:33,990 --> 00:08:34,890
I'm not going.

194
00:08:35,150 --> 00:08:37,030
They'll definitely show bananas again.

195
00:08:37,150 --> 00:08:39,970
You're the first person in the world who wants to skip sex ed.

196
00:08:42,350 --> 00:08:43,050
Saša?

197
00:08:43,550 --> 00:08:46,050
If you kill Lexa, I'll forge you a sick note.

198
00:08:56,470 --> 00:08:56,950
Dad.

199
00:08:57,470 --> 00:08:58,270
What?

200
00:08:58,750 --> 00:08:59,750
What is that?

201
00:08:59,950 --> 00:09:02,650
Do you want to read it in bed too?

202
00:09:02,950 --> 00:09:05,050
No, no, no, no.

203
00:09:05,150 --> 00:09:07,590
It just started getting interesting.

204
00:09:07,950 --> 00:09:09,550
Did the father already throw the apple at him?

205
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:10,760
What?

206
00:09:11,450 --> 00:09:13,250
Good night.

207
00:09:13,450 --> 00:09:14,450
Good night.

208
00:09:28,450 --> 00:09:29,350
Marcelka?

209
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:31,280
Come in, Tomáš.

210
00:09:31,920 --> 00:09:32,880
Excuse me?

211
00:09:36,050 --> 00:09:36,750
Thank you.

212
00:09:37,150 --> 00:09:42,250
Did something happen?

213
00:09:45,750 --> 00:09:47,750
I can no longer be your manager.

214
00:09:48,350 --> 00:09:49,150
But why?

215
00:09:50,350 --> 00:09:51,250
Because you're an oaf.

216
00:09:51,450 --> 00:09:54,150
Oh come on, Marcelka.

217
00:09:54,210 --> 00:09:55,170
An oaf.

218
00:09:56,250 --> 00:09:58,050
Everyone knows it.

219
00:09:59,850 --> 00:10:03,750
This is what Mirka sends us.

220
00:10:05,950 --> 00:10:06,750
This one.

221
00:10:07,850 --> 00:10:08,900
Dárka.

222
00:10:11,050 --> 00:10:13,840
And here. Věrka.

223
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:19,150
They laughed at me all evening.

224
00:10:20,350 --> 00:10:24,750
Come now, Marcelka, go home and get some sleep and tomorrow we can talk about it.

225
00:10:26,850 --> 00:10:28,050
Talk?

226
00:10:28,650 --> 00:10:32,120
That's exactly what's impossible with you, you...

227
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:33,580
Bogeyman.

228
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:38,050
What would you even want to talk about?

229
00:10:38,850 --> 00:10:42,050
You don't go to exhibitions, you fall asleep at the theater.

230
00:10:42,150 --> 00:10:47,350
And the only thing you've ever read was written by Dick Francis.

231
00:10:48,050 --> 00:10:50,550
I'll have you know I've been reading The Metamorphosis all day today.

232
00:10:58,350 --> 00:10:59,550
You're on page six.

233
00:11:00,850 --> 00:11:01,750
Hero.

234
00:11:08,950 --> 00:11:09,650
I'm leaving.

235
00:11:11,350 --> 00:11:11,950
Goodbye.

236
00:11:16,850 --> 00:11:17,850
Marcelka.

237
00:11:22,590 --> 00:11:23,150
Darn.

238
00:11:25,250 --> 00:11:26,850
Ozzák, watch out, Marcelka is there.

239
00:11:28,350 --> 00:11:30,210
Damn, all my cake stuff is in there.

240
00:11:36,550 --> 00:11:37,950
But it's way too early.

241
00:11:45,950 --> 00:11:48,250
What, I'm following the recipe exactly.

242
00:11:48,550 --> 00:11:49,750
Kitty has it in there.

243
00:11:51,750 --> 00:11:52,850
Is this about Marcelka?

244
00:11:53,810 --> 00:11:54,830
Ozzák ticked her off.

245
00:12:04,140 --> 00:12:04,740
Hey.

246
00:12:05,450 --> 00:12:06,450
What a night.

247
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:07,240
What happened?

248
00:12:08,850 --> 00:12:11,850
I felt like I was growing wing covers.

249
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:14,450
Is there some diet going on, or what?

250
00:12:15,350 --> 00:12:16,950
There was nothing else in the fridge.

251
00:12:17,650 --> 00:12:18,650
Ozzák is cooking something?

252
00:12:19,450 --> 00:12:21,840
Jesus, I forgot to forbid him.

253
00:12:22,250 --> 00:12:23,050
Is he up yet?

254
00:12:23,750 --> 00:12:24,240
He's gone.

255
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:25,850
And the electric roaster is missing.

256
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:29,360
Damn Doggy and Kitty.

257
00:12:31,840 --> 00:12:32,440
What is it?

258
00:12:33,260 --> 00:12:33,700
Nothing.

259
00:12:35,550 --> 00:12:37,180
Did you also read the interview?

260
00:12:37,350 --> 00:12:39,850
Yeah, they put it on the bulletin board at school.

261
00:12:40,750 --> 00:12:42,950
I really didn't say that about the bagpiper.

262
00:12:43,250 --> 00:12:46,760
Says the man who told me that Grandma had a sultan and a tiger.

263
00:12:46,760 --> 00:12:47,200
Right?

264
00:12:47,540 --> 00:12:49,740
I eventually knew the other one was also a dog.

265
00:12:49,920 --> 00:12:51,260
I just mixed up the names.

266
00:12:55,460 --> 00:12:55,900
Hey.

267
00:12:56,660 --> 00:12:57,500
I'll grab my bag.

268
00:13:05,050 --> 00:13:06,050
Uh, hi, Saša.

269
00:13:17,480 --> 00:13:17,920
Need something?

270
00:13:18,950 --> 00:13:21,360
Mom said you wanted to talk to me about something.

271
00:13:21,750 --> 00:13:22,550
Yeah, yeah.

272
00:13:22,890 --> 00:13:23,730
No, seriously.

273
00:13:23,810 --> 00:13:25,390
She said you wouldn't want to at first.

274
00:13:25,390 --> 00:13:29,950
But when I tell you that Iva could also find out who Auntie Marta is, you'll want to.

275
00:13:30,650 --> 00:13:34,010
I think I'll want to talk to your mother first.

276
00:13:34,010 --> 00:13:35,530
She said you'd say that too.

277
00:13:35,910 --> 00:13:36,970
Besides, I don't have time.

278
00:13:37,550 --> 00:13:38,550
She said that too.

279
00:13:40,150 --> 00:13:41,250
And what else did she say?

280
00:13:42,050 --> 00:13:44,700
That you'd probably want to run away, so I should lock the door behind me.

281
00:13:44,700 --> 00:13:45,880
But I didn't do that.

282
00:13:47,450 --> 00:13:48,450
Good girl.

283
00:14:04,860 --> 00:14:05,400
Marcelka!

284
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:07,350
Good morning, Tomáš.

285
00:14:07,950 --> 00:14:09,650
I'm glad to see you.

286
00:14:10,150 --> 00:14:11,850
We open at nine, don't we?

287
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:12,850
Well, last night...

288
00:14:13,050 --> 00:14:15,520
Forget about it, I lost my temper.

289
00:14:15,850 --> 00:14:19,450
Those hags got me so worked up that I brought it on with Thuringian pastries.

290
00:14:21,850 --> 00:14:23,950
The main ingredient is Thuringian rye.

291
00:14:25,300 --> 00:14:27,240
So you don't think I'm an oaf?

292
00:14:27,380 --> 00:14:29,280
Just because Kafka puts me to sleep?

293
00:14:29,950 --> 00:14:33,850
You are absolutely an oaf, but we need to try to disguise it.

294
00:14:34,160 --> 00:14:34,700
I see.

295
00:14:35,550 --> 00:14:36,450
So first of all.

296
00:14:36,750 --> 00:14:39,450
You'll listen to all of these.

297
00:14:40,050 --> 00:14:41,280
Classics with Humor?

298
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:41,740
What is it?

299
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:45,650
A collection of the most important books performed by popular comedians.

300
00:14:47,050 --> 00:14:50,350
The Old Man and the Sea retold by Luděk Sobota?

301
00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:56,010
Plus a bonus of the 20 best fish jokes?

302
00:14:56,150 --> 00:14:57,250
Perfect for you.

303
00:14:57,870 --> 00:15:00,990
This morning I listened to Ivan Mládek's Banjo Band plays Macbeth.

304
00:15:01,050 --> 00:15:03,650
I think you'll find it very entertaining.

305
00:15:03,850 --> 00:15:06,830
And who would have thought Shakespeare had so many songs?

306
00:15:08,550 --> 00:15:10,850
Silly me, I grabbed the wrong Macbeth.

307
00:15:11,050 --> 00:15:12,950
The Swan of Avon didn't write it.

308
00:15:14,150 --> 00:15:15,070
And did you say Swan?

309
00:15:15,350 --> 00:15:16,430
The Swan of Avon.

310
00:15:17,050 --> 00:15:18,650
That's what they call Shakespeare.

311
00:15:19,150 --> 00:15:19,950
But why?

312
00:15:20,650 --> 00:15:22,350
You know, I don't even know.

313
00:15:22,610 --> 00:15:24,010
Probably had a long neck.

314
00:15:24,010 --> 00:15:26,750
But I don't really feel like getting into this one.

315
00:15:27,190 --> 00:15:29,130
I'm not a huge fan of Suchánek and Genzer.

316
00:15:29,270 --> 00:15:31,230
But you have to know The Brothers Karamazov.

317
00:15:33,050 --> 00:15:33,750
Fine.

318
00:15:35,150 --> 00:15:36,390
And after I listen to them?

319
00:15:36,750 --> 00:15:39,250
You'll give Mirka an interview and we'll see how it goes.

320
00:15:39,390 --> 00:15:40,070
Which Mirka?

321
00:15:40,490 --> 00:15:40,950
Vostrá.

322
00:15:41,250 --> 00:15:43,450
Editor at Bruneta magazine.

323
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:46,150
And you think it'll work?

324
00:15:46,850 --> 00:15:48,950
She's convinced you're an idiot.

325
00:15:49,150 --> 00:15:50,650
You've got nothing to lose.

326
00:15:57,080 --> 00:15:59,480
Again, again, again, again.

327
00:15:59,480 --> 00:16:04,450
If you think it bothers me that much that you imagine me naked, you're wrong.

328
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:05,950
Naked.

329
00:16:06,950 --> 00:16:09,050
Yeah, now I can do naked too.

330
00:16:09,250 --> 00:16:11,850
Great, that's much better than when you're jumping on a trampoline.

331
00:16:13,830 --> 00:16:14,290
Oh my.

332
00:16:16,650 --> 00:16:18,650
Iva, I won't be able to handle it again tomorrow.

333
00:16:18,690 --> 00:16:21,290
You're like a little kid, don't you know anything about it?

334
00:16:21,610 --> 00:16:24,090
I do, I read about it in the biology textbook.

335
00:16:24,350 --> 00:16:26,090
Well then you know everything, there are even pictures.

336
00:16:26,250 --> 00:16:27,570
But only in cross section.

337
00:16:27,750 --> 00:16:28,770
What, you've never seen one?

338
00:16:28,990 --> 00:16:29,070
No.

339
00:16:30,050 --> 00:16:32,130
I thought you and Lexa bathed together.

340
00:16:32,350 --> 00:16:33,950
We bathe all the time.

341
00:16:34,850 --> 00:16:36,510
So what does Lexa have between his legs?

342
00:16:36,510 --> 00:16:36,990
Nothing.

343
00:16:38,450 --> 00:16:39,350
Nothing?

344
00:16:39,650 --> 00:16:42,250
Nothing from the picture, he just has a little willy.

345
00:16:42,350 --> 00:16:44,250
He definitely has vas deferens.

346
00:16:46,850 --> 00:16:48,650
Maybe the movie won't be so terrible.

347
00:16:48,950 --> 00:16:52,250
I think it'll be even worse than Cutting It Short.

348
00:16:53,150 --> 00:16:54,550
Well, that's possible.

349
00:16:55,500 --> 00:16:56,620
Iva, I'm not going.

350
00:16:56,620 --> 00:16:59,020
I'll get sick, maybe catch a cold.

351
00:16:59,250 --> 00:17:00,550
How, in this heat?

352
00:17:00,850 --> 00:17:02,550
I don't know, I'll think of something.

353
00:17:05,150 --> 00:17:06,020
What now?

354
00:17:06,250 --> 00:17:07,950
Iva, you're naked and on a trampoline.

355
00:17:10,450 --> 00:17:11,680
Ugh, you're a pig.

356
00:17:11,950 --> 00:17:13,380
I'm going to take a shower.

357
00:17:13,550 --> 00:17:15,650
Whoa, a shower?

358
00:17:16,450 --> 00:17:17,550
Don't you dare.

359
00:17:17,950 --> 00:17:18,400
Or what?

360
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:19,940
Or I'll imagine you instead.

361
00:17:20,340 --> 00:17:21,120
Go right ahead.

362
00:17:22,350 --> 00:17:24,850
Alright, you naked on a trampoline.

363
00:17:35,050 --> 00:17:36,730
Actually it wasn't even that funny.

364
00:17:36,730 --> 00:17:37,330
Iva.

365
00:17:38,450 --> 00:17:39,450
It was more... weird.

366
00:17:43,270 --> 00:17:54,600
What are you reading?

367
00:17:54,980 --> 00:17:56,000
The Gulag Archipelago.

368
00:17:56,300 --> 00:17:57,380
It's so funny.

369
00:17:57,380 --> 00:18:01,050
Yeah, it's done like jokes by Neprakta.

370
00:18:07,150 --> 00:18:07,910
Good afternoon.

371
00:18:12,250 --> 00:18:12,880
How are we doing?

372
00:18:13,250 --> 00:18:14,750
Well, I listened to everything.

373
00:18:15,350 --> 00:18:16,950
Except for Petr Novotný.

374
00:18:17,150 --> 00:18:17,750
Idiot.

375
00:18:17,770 --> 00:18:18,370
Right.

376
00:18:18,670 --> 00:18:19,270
Doesn't matter.

377
00:18:19,850 --> 00:18:24,850
If you heard the Karamazovs and at least two sketches from War and Peace, we have Russian classics covered.

378
00:18:25,260 --> 00:18:26,940
Marcelka, I don't know, I don't feel like it.

379
00:18:26,940 --> 00:18:30,120
Mirka is coming tomorrow morning, there's no turning back.

380
00:18:30,450 --> 00:18:33,150
And what if she realizes I didn't actually read them?

381
00:18:33,550 --> 00:18:35,950
Sometimes it does seem a bit too adapted.

382
00:18:36,450 --> 00:18:39,550
Really, did the Brothers Karamazov fart that often?

383
00:18:40,850 --> 00:18:44,070
If worst comes to worst, say you saw it at the New Stage.

384
00:18:44,070 --> 00:18:46,030
They also do classics there, just more fresh.

385
00:18:47,890 --> 00:18:50,310
And couldn't it be done in writing?

386
00:18:50,310 --> 00:18:53,530
I can't formulate complicated things well in face-to-face conversation.

387
00:18:53,950 --> 00:18:54,950
We know.

388
00:18:55,250 --> 00:18:56,050
Stop it.

389
00:18:56,350 --> 00:18:59,030
I just don't want Ivuška to read something either.

390
00:18:59,030 --> 00:19:00,970
Well, that won't hurt anyone.

391
00:19:01,030 --> 00:19:02,230
I have something for her.

392
00:19:02,750 --> 00:19:05,650
It's called Auntie Marta.

393
00:19:06,450 --> 00:19:08,410
That's something like Old Goriot.

394
00:19:08,690 --> 00:19:10,170
More like Father Weirdo.

395
00:19:10,250 --> 00:19:10,710
Enough.

396
00:19:11,250 --> 00:19:13,590
I just want to remind you that you have another conversation ahead.

397
00:19:13,590 --> 00:19:14,410
With whom?

398
00:19:14,410 --> 00:19:15,550
With no one.

399
00:19:16,150 --> 00:19:17,070
He's stubborn as a mule.

400
00:19:17,070 --> 00:19:18,290
Tell me about it.

401
00:19:18,290 --> 00:19:19,850
But in the end...

402
00:19:20,050 --> 00:19:21,760
He always does it anyway.

403
00:19:21,760 --> 00:19:23,120
He has no other choice.

404
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:25,200
Mirka refuses written interviews.

405
00:19:25,650 --> 00:19:26,550
But don't worry.

406
00:19:27,250 --> 00:19:28,350
You'll manage.

407
00:19:28,650 --> 00:19:30,050
Forget the jokes and just talk about the essentials.

408
00:19:31,910 --> 00:19:32,490
My thoughts exactly.

409
00:19:32,910 --> 00:19:36,890
And besides, tonight is the Thuringian conceptualism opening.

410
00:19:36,890 --> 00:19:42,690
And if the pastries are as strong as they were at the surrealism event, Mirka will still be weakened in the morning.

411
00:19:45,450 --> 00:19:46,550
So I already put it in.

412
00:19:46,950 --> 00:19:51,450
If you destroy the electric roaster, don't worry, it'll cool through your nose.

413
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:53,150
And in the morning we'll have a feast.

414
00:19:53,650 --> 00:19:55,250
Don't count on me eating it.

415
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:56,450
Why not?

416
00:19:56,650 --> 00:19:58,550
I don't eat anything that has mice in it.

417
00:19:58,560 --> 00:20:00,380
No, Lída, why would I put a mouse in there?

418
00:20:00,460 --> 00:20:01,460
We slept together in bed.

419
00:20:03,650 --> 00:20:05,120
Just as friends.

420
00:20:05,550 --> 00:20:07,750
Recipe or no recipe, you don't put a friend in a cake.

421
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:13,350
So instead of her I put in stuff that I like.

422
00:20:13,750 --> 00:20:15,150
That the kitty didn't have.

423
00:20:16,220 --> 00:20:16,640
How much?

424
00:20:17,350 --> 00:20:19,240
Three bottles of rum and one absinthe.

425
00:20:19,650 --> 00:20:21,750
And you think I'm paying for this?

426
00:20:22,050 --> 00:20:22,950
Probably.

427
00:20:23,450 --> 00:20:26,880
The thing is, Ozzák here also knows Auntie Marta.

428
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:28,340
Even Ozzák?

429
00:20:28,540 --> 00:20:29,280
You bet.

430
00:20:31,150 --> 00:20:33,370
I guess I should read it too.

431
00:20:34,250 --> 00:20:35,150
Who wrote it?

432
00:20:36,890 --> 00:20:38,050
Father Weirdo.

433
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:50,520
'Twas evening May, the time of love, the turtledove's soft cooing calls to love.

434
00:20:50,520 --> 00:21:01,950
And watch those bottoms, breathe regularly, Hinka, Vilém, Jarmila, on the box, off the box, and up and down.

435
00:21:02,450 --> 00:21:09,750
Now let's just catch our breath and next time for Czech poetry of the nineteenth century with me, Olga Šípková, see you again.

436
00:21:10,050 --> 00:21:10,850
What are you doing?

437
00:21:18,290 --> 00:21:19,470
I'm rushing to that interview.

438
00:21:19,670 --> 00:21:20,430
You went overboard.

439
00:21:20,950 --> 00:21:21,470
What?

440
00:21:22,250 --> 00:21:24,350
I wanted you to just tell her the basics.

441
00:21:25,140 --> 00:21:25,660
What?

442
00:21:25,660 --> 00:21:27,950
Like, that boys are different down there, how it works.

443
00:21:28,150 --> 00:21:29,770
You had to go straight for the advanced stuff.

444
00:21:29,950 --> 00:21:31,190
What are you talking about?

445
00:21:31,550 --> 00:21:32,350
About Saša.

446
00:21:32,750 --> 00:21:34,750
This morning I found her in the fridge.

447
00:21:35,050 --> 00:21:37,250
For God's sake, what does that have to do with me?

448
00:21:37,370 --> 00:21:41,710
So right away you tell her about those extreme things and then you're surprised the girl wants to try it.

449
00:21:41,870 --> 00:21:44,110
Excuse me, I didn't talk to her about it at all.

450
00:21:44,850 --> 00:21:46,210
And what did you want to try?

451
00:21:46,450 --> 00:21:51,050
Well, we all have our things, but I thought you were more into the classics.

452
00:21:51,550 --> 00:21:54,130
Look, Simona, I don't have time now, let's talk about it later, okay?

453
00:21:54,130 --> 00:21:55,090
Yours is spacious, isn't it?

454
00:21:56,650 --> 00:21:59,850
Poor little Saša had to curl up in ours.

455
00:22:00,450 --> 00:22:03,850
Simona, I don't do it in the fridge.

456
00:22:04,450 --> 00:22:06,170
Then why are you putting ideas in young girls' heads?

457
00:22:06,550 --> 00:22:07,730
What if she gets hooked on it?

458
00:22:07,730 --> 00:22:09,710
I can't afford a fridge that big.

459
00:22:09,870 --> 00:22:11,110
You want our fridge?

460
00:22:11,870 --> 00:22:14,430
If you got me hooked on it, how is that fair to me?

461
00:22:14,950 --> 00:22:16,790
But I didn't talk to her about it at all.

462
00:22:17,050 --> 00:22:18,250
Well, now you'll have to.

463
00:22:18,740 --> 00:22:19,860
Otherwise you're giving up the fridge.

464
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:21,380
This is insane.

465
00:22:21,440 --> 00:22:22,880
This is like something by Kafka.

466
00:22:24,600 --> 00:22:25,080
Good lord.

467
00:22:25,080 --> 00:22:27,940
Ostrá, Simona, I really have to go to that interview now.

468
00:22:28,150 --> 00:22:29,550
Go ahead, I'll lock up.

469
00:22:38,850 --> 00:22:39,950
Nicely cleaned out.

470
00:22:40,750 --> 00:22:42,550
Someone was planning to have fun in here today.

471
00:22:51,850 --> 00:22:53,350
When do you think he'll come?

472
00:22:53,440 --> 00:22:54,320
What do you want from him?

473
00:22:55,450 --> 00:22:57,450
I'm here to do an interview with him.

474
00:22:59,240 --> 00:23:00,440
Here, behind the pool table?

475
00:23:00,960 --> 00:23:01,880
Are you Vostrá?

476
00:23:02,650 --> 00:23:03,080
Yes.

477
00:23:03,080 --> 00:23:03,760
And you are?

478
00:23:04,650 --> 00:23:05,150
Why?

479
00:23:06,350 --> 00:23:07,850
Would you like to do it with me too?

480
00:23:08,240 --> 00:23:08,660
No.

481
00:23:10,050 --> 00:23:11,750
Good, I was getting worried.

482
00:23:14,700 --> 00:23:16,640
So when will Mr. Pacovský actually come?

483
00:23:16,640 --> 00:23:20,250
If I'd known he'd be this late, I could have gone to the opening last night.

484
00:23:21,550 --> 00:23:22,550
Phew, he'll be here soon!

485
00:23:23,250 --> 00:23:25,150
I baked something and I want him to taste it.

486
00:23:27,590 --> 00:23:28,070
Well then.

487
00:23:29,150 --> 00:23:29,950
What is it?

488
00:23:30,850 --> 00:23:32,550
Thuringian pastry.

489
00:23:32,950 --> 00:23:34,150
By Mr. Kitty's recipe.

490
00:23:34,390 --> 00:23:34,930
Would you like some?

491
00:23:47,350 --> 00:23:48,850
So how was school?

492
00:23:49,480 --> 00:23:51,540
Mom, the movie was beautiful.

493
00:23:51,740 --> 00:23:52,940
It was pretty dumb.

494
00:23:53,080 --> 00:23:54,520
No, it was actually interesting.

495
00:23:54,620 --> 00:23:57,380
See, and this morning I had to drag you there by the hand.

496
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:00,100
There were flowers, little bees, and little rabbits.

497
00:24:00,980 --> 00:24:02,000
And nothing else?

498
00:24:02,850 --> 00:24:06,220
Well, they were saying something else too, but I had my ears plugged just in case.

499
00:24:06,220 --> 00:24:06,680
I see.

500
00:24:07,550 --> 00:24:08,950
Pretty dumb movie.

501
00:24:09,750 --> 00:24:11,350
It's true I wouldn't go a second time.

502
00:24:11,400 --> 00:24:11,840
Right.

503
00:24:12,250 --> 00:24:15,050
When I close my eyes now, I just see stupid bees.

504
00:24:15,780 --> 00:24:16,240
Great.

505
00:24:19,030 --> 00:24:20,610
I still see you.

506
00:24:23,550 --> 00:24:25,350
Oh, there you are.

507
00:24:26,350 --> 00:24:27,250
How did the interview go?

508
00:24:28,340 --> 00:24:28,800
Great.

509
00:24:29,850 --> 00:24:33,050
Vostrá ate something bad and is in the hospital.

510
00:24:33,950 --> 00:24:35,750
I'm answering in writing.

511
00:24:36,550 --> 00:24:39,650
Iva, but my favorite novel?

512
00:24:41,350 --> 00:24:42,350
The Red and the Black.

513
00:24:44,330 --> 00:24:44,970
Yeah?

514
00:24:46,350 --> 00:24:47,750
I don't know which one to pick.

515
00:24:48,230 --> 00:24:48,870
Same.

516
00:24:48,990 --> 00:24:49,850
That was a joke!

517
00:24:51,650 --> 00:24:54,350
I'll put Don Quixote.

518
00:24:55,550 --> 00:24:57,170
Tomáš, it's Saša.

519
00:24:57,170 --> 00:24:57,910
Simona, stop it.

520
00:24:58,450 --> 00:25:03,610
Well, if you want Ivuška to find out something interesting about your fridge, then...

521
00:25:03,650 --> 00:25:05,250
Simona, leave me alone, please?

522
00:25:05,550 --> 00:25:07,790
I'm simply not going to deal with these things for you.

523
00:25:09,150 --> 00:25:10,650
Fine then, I could have saved a kilo.

524
00:25:10,670 --> 00:25:11,370
Oven!

525
00:25:12,450 --> 00:25:12,850
I'm only on page 30.

526
00:25:16,470 --> 00:25:17,070
That's enough.

527
00:25:17,350 --> 00:25:19,010
Just the basics, understand?

528
00:25:30,850 --> 00:25:33,950
But excuse me, you're not Mr. Samsa.

529
00:25:34,060 --> 00:25:34,760
What?

530
00:25:34,920 --> 00:25:35,880
That I'm not?

531
00:25:37,650 --> 00:25:43,450
No, I know Gregor Samsa, but you look like some kind of bug.

532
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:44,800
Like a bug?

533
00:25:47,410 --> 00:25:48,030
Completely.

534
00:25:48,030 --> 00:25:50,750
Wing covers, antennae and all.

535
00:25:51,370 --> 00:25:52,170
Antennae?

536
00:25:53,950 --> 00:25:54,850
Well yes.

537
00:25:55,550 --> 00:25:58,750
Well then, shall we switch to first names?

538
00:26:07,510 --> 00:26:09,310
Can't you see I'm admiring you?
